<item>
            <title>[ZOOKEEPER-1843] Oddity in ByteBufferInputStream skip</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/ZOOKEEPER-1843</link>
                <project id="12310801" key="ZOOKEEPER">ZooKeeper</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;I was reading ByteBufferInputStream.java; here is the skip method:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;    public long skip(long n) throws IOException {&lt;br/&gt;
        long newPos = bb.position() + n;&lt;br/&gt;
        if (newPos &amp;gt; bb.remaining()) &lt;/p&gt;
{
            n = bb.remaining();
        }
&lt;p&gt;        bb.position(bb.position() + (int) n);&lt;br/&gt;
        return n;&lt;br/&gt;
    }&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The first two lines look wrong; we compare a &quot;point&quot; (position) to a &quot;distance&quot; (remaining).  I think the test should be if (newPos &amp;gt;= bb.limit()).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Or more simply:&lt;br/&gt;
    public long skip(long n) throws IOException {&lt;br/&gt;
        int remaining = buffer.remaining();&lt;br/&gt;
        if (n &amp;gt; remaining) &lt;/p&gt;
{
            n = remaining;
        }
&lt;p&gt;        buffer.position(buffer.position() + (int) n);&lt;br/&gt;
        return n;&lt;br/&gt;
    }&lt;/p&gt;</description>
